From: James L. Alexander, DVM, MPVM <DrJames.Alexander@tdh.state.tx.us>

Here's some more info. I asked him about asbestos exposure and this is his
reply. I've also posed the occupation question and will forward when
received.
Since his house is circa 1940-1950 era I suspect lead may have been in the
plaster, wall board and/or paint. Lead may well be a consideration. I've
asked him to check with his MD about lead testing.
--
James L. Alexander, DVM, MPVM
e-mail: DrJames.Alexander@tdh.state.tx.us

(Patient's reply)
Date: Thu, 30 Jul 1998 11:14:52 -0400
Jim,
Yes, I was exposed to large amounts of asbestos (about 50 lbs) six months
prior to my symptoms when I removed it from my heating pipes in the
basement of my house. I wore an asbestos rated respirator and attempted to
clean up the dust on the floor as best as possible after removal. I do
remember getting some in my eyes occasionally. I took a shower immediately
afterward and wore long sleeves and long pants which were also washed
immediately afterward. The wallboard removed during the renovation was
fairly old (1940's or 50's) and had taped seems. I used an ordinary fiber
dust mask for the removal of the guano and wallboard.
For the last ten years I've been working in the finance industry with
emphasis on asset trading, software modeling and database management. I
spend about 10 hours a day at work on my computer.
No, I have not been tested for lead or asbestos poisoning. I've added those
to my list.
(Patient's Name Withheld)
