[2
Date: Thu, 30 Jul 1998 13:59:08 -0400
From: Paul Lehmann <pflehmann@mco.edu>

Histoplasmosis needs to be ruled out. It is not true to say that the CNS is
not invaded by _Histoplasma capsulatum_. Though CNS infection appears
uncommon in histoplasmosis, probably being found in less than 5% of severe
cases, it is by no means unknown. References to the condition can be found
in the monograph: J. Schwarz. 1981. Histoplasmosis. New York: Praeger.
In my view, it would be very much more likely for an immunocompetent person
to acquire histoplasmosis from bat guano than to acquire cryptococcosis.
Indeed, we see histoplasmosis cases with such exposure fairly regularly. As
far as I know, _Cryptococcus neoformans_ is not associated with bat guano.
--
Paul F. Lehmann, Ph.D.
Department of Microbiology and Immunology
Medical College of Ohio at Toledo
e-mail: PFLehmann@mco.edu
